  "prompt": "If light has no mass, how can a solar sail be propelled?",
  "response": "A solar sail is propelled by the momentum of photons (light particles) from the sun, despite photons having no rest mass. This works through the principle of radiation pressure. Here's how:\n\n1. Photons carry momentum, even though they have no rest mass. According to Einstein's special relativity, photons have momentum based on their energy and wavelength.\n\n2. When photons bounce off or are absorbed by the highly reflective surface of a solar sail, they transfer their momentum to the sail.\n\n3. Each individual photon transfer is extremely small, but when millions of photons continuously strike the sail, the cumulative momentum creates a gentle but continuous acceleration.\n\n4. The sail is typically made of extremely thin, lightweight, and highly reflective material like Mylar or aluminum to maximize the momentum transfer and minimize the sail's own mass.\n\n5. In the vacuum of space, where there's no friction, this continuous tiny acceleration can gradually build up to significant velocity over time.\n\nThis concept has been demonstrated by missions like Japan's IKAROS spacecraft and NASA's NanoSail-D2, which successfully used solar sail technology for propulsion.\n\nThe key principle is that momentum can be transferred without the transferring particle (photon) having rest mass, based on the relationship between energy, momentum, and the speed of light in Einstein's equations.",
